column168: The employee was filling underground tank, when it got to 50% it shut off at 442.4sgallons. The gauge read 50% at that moment, the relief valve discharged, failed. column169: Make sure the tank is buried with the valve assemblies above final grade to minimize flooding, inspection of relief valve must be done safely using mirror during annual inspections. Make sure relief valve cap or rain covers is in place to keep debris from getting into opening. Insure weep holes at base of the relief valve are clear to allow moisture to drain.

column168: The driver finished loading around 6pm on the 10/6/2015. As he was headed southbound on Interstate 35, our driver was notified by another truck driver that he had started leaking at mile marker 157. The driver pulled over at mile marker 154 at 9:30 pm by 10:00 pm the driver had stopped the leak. At 11:00 pm hazmat and the Iowa highway patrol arrived and deemed the spill was contained and determined there was no risk or danger. We contacted our cleanup and remediation crew, who came to power wash the spill off the highway and remove the contaminated soil.     We determined that the spill was caused by a damaged site tube that allowed the ball valve to leak.
column169: We have instructed all of our drivers to inspect all possible points of failure and that all drivers must be familiar with M&M Environmental Group's spill containment procedures.

column168: At 2145 hours on October 7, 2015 I, John Vergis, was called by the Wheeling and Lake Erie Brewster Yardmaster about a car UTLX950924 that was reported leaking on the west end of 10 track in Brewster Yard.  When I got there and investigated, I found that this car was indeed leaking from the liquid valve on the B end of the car.  The valve was frosted over and leaking liquid.  I tried to tighten the valve handle a little more to see if the leak would stop and it did not.  I tightened the valve plug which was less than tool tight and was able to stop the leak.  Took old seal 070672 off and installed new seal 00249468.  The shipper was going to submit for a movement approval and move back to their facility for offloading and then send to home shop for repair. Responsible associate has been shown proper freight handling and loading techniques as well as recertified for forklift operation.  Responsible associate has been shown proper freight handling and loading techniques.

Old seal was 018660 and new seal was 00249361.

column168: During dock operation, an apparent forklift puncture resulted in the release of approximately 1 quart of a UN1133 Flammable Adhesive (Stabond E-183) from a 5 gallon plastic pail on the concrete dock floor only. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted by this release. Terminal personnel over packed the damaged pail and staged it on site pending the shipper's disposition. The fuel truck driver was attempting to pump out a temporary 1000 gallon aboveground storage tank at a jobsite. The driver used a hose to remove the fuel from the tank and through partial equipment malfunction and human error the fuel was sucked out of the tank too quickly and spilled onto the ground. Approximately 50 gallons of dyed diesel fuel ran into a storm ditch along the road. The ditch was filled with water from rain in the area and the fuel ran approximately 1000 feet in the ditch. A lake is located at the end of the road but the fuel did not reach the lake. The incident was reported to the State (SCDHEC) and the NRC due to proximity to water. The driver used absorbent pads and boom at the scene initially. The spill responder arrived later that day to remove the product from the ditch via vac truck. The spill responder will remove the soil and test to ensure fuel is removed from the ground. We are working with the state (SCDHEC) on the cleanup and removal.
column169: Great Lakes Petro will work with drivers to ensure incidents like this do not occur in the future.

column168: October 1, 2015; 11:24PM:  Call received by CR Risk Manager A. Richter from Detroit Terminal Manager Field Operations K. Johnson, that tank car UTLX 130175, load, Hydrochloric Acid, was noted to have "puffed out smoke" while car was being switched in CR's North Yard facility, Detroit, MI (serving yard for intended customer, PVS).    Car isolated to track #6 in the yard.  Further inspection by CR Emergency response contractor SunPro, found the Safety Relief device (non-reclosing) was missing the safety vent rupture disc (165#), the surge protection system inside the safety vent assembly; and, the inspection/closure plug for the safety vent assembly was not secured and hanging off to the side.    SunPro responders removed the assembly, and reapplied a new complete assembly, supplied by the original intended customer, PVS.  Car was also decontaminated on top and sides, with no report of product contacting the ground.    Car moved under authority of an OTMA-3, Defect No. 5, to original customer, for unloading.  Customer will have the required pressure leak test performed at their location after car has been unloaded.

column162: ASST. DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: At 18:15 MST, UPRR Dispatch reported to the BNSF ROCC that the H-DENPVO1-02A was leaking gasoline from the UTLX 203036 on Union Pacific Moffat Tunnel Subdivision near Milepost 22.44.  Union Pacific Contractor responded to the car and identified the Liquid Line Valve as failed with a small amount of gasoline bypassing the closed liquid line valve and coming through the threads on the quick connect closure on top of the valve.  Union Pacific Contractor re-secured the liquid line closure with new Teflon tape and tool tightened the fitting.  All spilled material evaporated from the car body, no liquid was observed to reach the ground.  BNSF removed the car from the train in Parachute, CO and notified the shipper that further movement would require an OTMA.  The "quantity released" in this report is an estimate based upon information provided by the responders who secured this car.
column169: Shipper should ensure that all fittings and closures are in proper condition to avoid spillage while in transportation.  This includes ensuring that all closures are properly functioning and in the closed position and that all threaded connections are sealed and tightened using a suitable tool.

column168: At approximately 1750 CT on October 12, 2015 BNSF mechanical personnel at the repair facility in Barstow, CA reported tank car UTLX 201262 leaking from the top combination housing from the liquid valve at a rate of 1 gallon per hour.  The car is a placarded load of methanol and the liquid was evaporating from the side of the tank car and not hitting the ground.  BNSF hazmat responder investigated and found the liquid valve 1/2 turn loose allowing product to leak from the nipple between the valve and the car.  Using a 24" pipe wrench, the valve was secured and the leak was stopped.  The car was monitored for a period of time to ensure stoppage and to observe the methanol fully evaporating from the car body.The car was released for service to continue to destination.
column169: Shippers and loaders must ensure that all valves, fittings, closures are properly secured prior to releasing into transport.  This process should be periodically and randomly audited to ensure compliance.  Re-training and employee accountability should occur as appropriate.

column168: At approximately 1330 hours on October 13, 2015 BNSF Barstow mechanical inspectors found the DBUX 301997, a load of alcohols n.o.s. leaking on track 1201 in the Barstow trainyard from the bottom outlet valve.  BNSF hazmat responders inspected the car and found the bottom outlet valve handle closed and pinned, the outlet cap and plug securely fastened, but liquid was still leaking.  The responders cycled the valve handle several times in an attempt to clear any debris in the ball valve seat and observed the outlet cap for several minutes. The leak stopped at that point.  Then the responders removed the bottom outlet cap to inspect the gasket and found a large cut along the lateral surface.  The gasket was replaced and cap was re-secured.  The product evaporated on contact with the ground and the release was described as a slow drip with an estimate of 16 ounces or less lost.  The closures were all tightened and the car was no longer leaking; it was released to continue in service.
column169: Loading personnel should examine all closures and gaskets for proper tightness and fitness for transportation prior to offering into service.  Management should randomly audit this process to ensure quality and pursue accountability or retraining of personnel as necessary to prevent future non-accident caused releases.

The employee disconnected the hose and did not wait long enough for the liquid to bleed off before unhooking the hose and liquid propane sprayed out and hit him in the stomach area and on his right arm resulting in 1st degree burn to right arm and 2nd degree burn to abdomen area. The employee was treated and released at Family Medical Center. Told to keep wound dressing clean and dry. No lost time from work, no property damage.
column169: Have gone over the procedure for disconnecting a hose and have done an on vehicle supervision ride to make sure these procedures are followed.

column168: DBUX 250275 was pulled from Houston Fuel Oil Terminal and moved to PTRA North Yard to be held for product testing for high levels of H2S.  On 10/15/2015 the car was observed with product running down the sides from the manway. M&M Protection was on scene and inspected the tank car. They found that three manway bolts were not tightened and the manway gasket was worn. They replaced the gasket and tightened and sealed the manway. The following morning M&M Protection pressure washed the exterior of the tank with a micro bug solution. The shipper was notified via email on 10/15 of their failure to properly secure the car for transport.
column169: Houston Fuel Oil Terminal has been notified of the failure. We are awaiting an action plan from them to prevent future occurrences.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On October 4, 2015 at 18:23 hours personnel in the CSX Howell Yard discovered GATX 70285, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Mosaic Fertilizer LLC, was notified (CHEMTREC Report # 2015-10-04-00053). Summit Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the frangible disc in the non-reclosing pressure relief device had ruptured.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative Gustav Navar.  Contractor personnel installed a new frangible disc. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.     NARRI: 2(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 40  Cause Code: 1004
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On October 6, 2015 FRA hazmat inspector was performing inspections at the CSXT Hopewell Yard, discovered PROX 61210, a loaded tank car of molten Sulphur leaking from the top of the car. The inspector noted a loose plug on a liquid line and a small amount of product spilled on flange. The car was isolated and the shipper Irving Oil Sharon Carey (Mike Lawson Chemtrade),  NRC ( Report #1130243), VA EMA (Report# HMVA-142728) were notified. Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the 2" liquid line valve plug less than tool tight and less than 1 pint of material spilled. Contractor removed the spilled material and placed back in car and made plug tool tight.     The leak was secured and the car released for transport.     NARRI=119  5(5+1+0)X(2+0)=60
column169: No additional comments.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: On October 12, 2015 at 11:20 personnel at 318 Blount St Fayetteville, N.C. discovered GLNX 33566, a loaded tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gas (Propane) leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper Ohio Valley Mid Stream, Fayetteville Fire Department, Fayetteville Police Department and CHEMTREC Report # 2015-1012-00098 were notified. HMS Robert James, a CSXT hazardous materials manager was dispatched to the scene and found that there is a hole in the bottom of the tank car. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Chris Hanlon. The Propane was transferred to another tank car UTLX 956184. This incident did require a special switching move.      NAR Cause Code: 652 - Tank / Shell / Crack - Weld Failure    2 (5+5+0) X (4+4)= 160 NARRI
column169: No additional comments.

column168: TILX 262011 was observed leaking from the manway area on the sides of the tank car on October 1, 2015 at approximately 1130 hours. Shell Chemical was notified of the leak and dispatched ES&H Services to the scene. Inspection of the car found that three of the manway bolts were less than tool tight allowing product to bypass the gasket and splash down the sides of the tank when the car was switched in the rail yard. Less than a gallon of product was determined to spill on the sides of the tank. ES&H inspected and secured the manway and the car was released at approximately 1300 hours.
column169: Shell Chemical was notified and responded immediately to the NAR.  They are investigating further to determine the reason for the loose bolts on the manway.

column168: On October 7, 2015, at 17:46 hours, Mechanical Foreman at the CSXT Queensgate Terminal, Cincinnati, Ohio reported that an unknown odor was discovered in the departure yard tracks. Upon inspection the odor was traced to tank car UTLX 67449, a residue tank car of Turpentine. The shipper, Renessenz Inc., was notified via Chemtrec, report #2015-10-07-00279. It was found that the vacuum relief valve (VRV) was releasing vapor.  The (VRV) was removed and replaced with a threaded plug. The shipper representative, John M. Hinson, 904 924 2853 was notified of the situation. Renessenz has filed a One Time Movement Approval 3 to send to home shop for appropriate repairs and requalification.    NARRI: 5x(4+1+0)x(2+0) = 50  Cause code:1122

column168: The IBC release was from a fire that occurred due to a mechanical failure of either the brakes on the trailer or a tire.  The fire breached the trailer and got into the cargo which resulted in the compromise of the IBC containers.  The IBC containers had the gaskets melted out of the gravity flow valve and also the center bung of each.  This container breach increased the fuel load of the fire.  The fire was extinguished with water only by local fire company.  Clean up company dispatched to clean up freight loss and trailer.  The IBC were melted and blackened from the fire and no identification markings could be identified.  The remaining material is being pumped, drummed and disposed of properly by clean up company.
column169: At this time the cause is under investigation but probably will not ever be 100% sure due to damage to trailer.

column168: This shipment was offered to Hapag-Lloyd from Los Angeles, California on the Seaspan Dalian Voyage 10E37 as non-hazardous cargo. Our Hamburg, Germany office thru our "Watchdog" program caught the potential undeclared cargo.  We inquired with the shipper regarding the B/L commodity showing as "cilindro CO2".  They confirmed that CO2 canisters were, in fact, loaded in the container. To this date, our customer advises that they are unable to provide a IMO Dangerous Goods form.  The packer is not certified, therefore, the shipper is refusing to provide or sign a hazardous declaration. The original shipping papers that accompanied the container did not indicate the presence of hazardous materials and the container was not placarded and/or marked. Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the vessel accordingly.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Driver positioned cargo tank motor vehicle for unloading fuel into a retain station underground storage tank.  The UST capacity is 15017 liquid gallons.  The driver made proper connections of vapor recovery hose and product delivery hose.  The driver opened product delivery valve to first click (75 gpm flow rate).  Driver made visual inspection for leakage and found none.  Driver increased gpm flow rate to maximum flow rate of 350 gpm. Within 30 seconds of maximum product flow, driver detected product overflowing the inlet spill capture bucket.  The driver immediately stopped product flow and deployed spill containment materials onto the spilled product.  A small amount of product flowed across a portion of the driveway and across three lanes of roadway (Oracle Road).  Emergency response personnel were contacted.  The emergency response personnel rerouted motor vehicle traffic around the roadway surface that contained the product.  A HM clean up team provided driveway/roadway cleaning.    Later inspection of the UST revealed that the check valve located in the inlet fill tube appeared to be faulty.  The check valve did not open completely as product flowed down the inlet tube.  This obstruction caused the product to "back up" the inlet tube and spill from the top of the inlet onto the surface of the driveway.    We have made numerous phone calls to the fire department and AZ DOT to obtain and bills for services rendered.  The authorities have not provided any documents related to the response services.
column169: The underground storage tank equipment should receive a higher level of inspection to assure that the check valve is operating correctly during product unloading into the UST.    Our drivers are reminded to follow proper procedure and monitor product flow during loading/unloading process.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On 10/20/2015 at 0554 hours personnel in the CSXT Rocky Mount Yard discovered GATX 2037, a loaded tank car of Fluorosilicic acid leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper Gus Navar (Mosaic), North Carolina Division of Emergency Management, National Response Center and CHEMTREC Report # 2015-1020-0040 were notified. HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the car was missing the rupture disc. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Gus Navar Ph 904-571-2953. Contractor personnel fixed the problem, replaced the rupture disk and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car required a bubble leak test before being released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.     NAR Cause Code: 1005 - Non - Reclosing Pressure Relief Device    5 ( 5 + 5 + 0 ) X ( 2 + 0 ) = 80

column168: On 10/21/15 at 1005 hours personnel in the CSXT Gentilly Yard located in New Orleans, LA, discovered GATX579869, a loaded tank car of 2-DIMETHYLAMINOETHANOL to be leaking from the bottom outlet valve area. The car was isolated and the shipper, Taminco and Eastman Chemcial Corp, was notified. United States Environmental Services, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and discovered that 2 of 8 bottom outlet valve flange bolts to be missing. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Chris Markerson, Eastman Chemical, 225-936-1925). Eastman dispatched ARI (Certified mobile repair facility) and they installed the 2 missing BOV flange bolts. The leak was secured and a bubble leak test was conducted on the car. The car passed all tests and ARI, certified mobile repair company, recertified and requalified this car and advised that is was now safe for transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move.      NAR Cause Code: 536  Bottom Outlet Valve- Mounting Flange Bolts/nuts missing    5(5+3+5) x (2+0) = 130 NARRI     Brewton, Alabama  10/21/15  GATX79869  2-DIMETHYLAMINOETHANOL

column168: A ROLL-OFF TRUCK AND TRAILER OPERATED BY CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES INC. WAS LOADING A ROLL-OFF CONTAINER AT A CLEAN HARBORS FACILITY AT CLIVE, UT. DURING THE COURSE OF LOADING THE CONTENTS SHIFTED AND FLOWED OVER THE REAR OF THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER AND SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE LOADING PROCEDURE. THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER WAS THEN PLACED BACK ONTO THE GROUND. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. A CLEANUP CREW WAS SUMMONED, DONNED THE PROPER PPE AND THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER AND THE ROLL OFF WAS SECURED. THE ROLL-OFF WAS THEN RELOADED ONTO THE TRUCK WITHOUT INCIDENT AND DELIVERED TO THE FINAL DISPOSAL DESTINATION. THE UTAH DIVISION OF RESPONSE & REMEDIATION PROVIDED REPORT #12393.
column169: THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INTERMODAL ROLL-OFF CONTAINING EXCESS FREE LIQUIDS AND ADVISED OF THE PROPER LOADING PARAMETERS FOR THE CONTAINER INVOLVED. THE SHIPPER HAS ALSO BEEN ADVISED TO INSPECT ALL OUTBOUND CONTAINERS FOR EXCESS FREE LIQUID. THE DRIVER HAS BEEN ADVISED TO INSPECT THE LOAD CONDITION FOR OVERLOADING, UNEVEN LOADING OR EXCESS FREE LIQUIDS PRIOR TO LOADING ANY ROLL-OFF CONTAINER AND REJECT CONTAINERS THAT HAVE BEEN LOADED IMPROPERLY. THE INBOUND CLEAN HARBORS TRANSFER FACILITY HAS ALSO BEEN ADVISED TO INSPECT ALL INBOUND INTERMODAL CONTAINERS FOR PROPER LOADING CONDITIONS PRIOR TO RELEASING THEM FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION.

column168: During the loading process a Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. driver overfilled the vessel and hose and caused a release when he attempted to removed the hose at the completion of loading. Dispatch and facility personnel were notified and an in house response crew was summoned. The response crew donned the proper PPE and cleaned the released material. The associated clean up materials were containerized and disposed of properly. The Utah Department of Environmental Quality was notified. Report # 12402.
column169: An internal investigation was conducted and it was determined that the cause of the release was directly related to the failure of the driver to properly monitor the loading process and fully clear, cap and control the hose at the conclusion of the loading process. The driver will be disciplined per company policy TC2.1 for failing to follow proper loading/unloading procedures. The driver will also be retrained on proper loading/unloading procedures. The driver will not be authorized to operate any CTMV for Clean Harbors pending completion and verification of retraining.

On October 30, 2015 at 1715 ET, two 50-lb plastic bags were torn open which resulted in a release of approximately 10 lbs. The cause was due to inadequate blocking and bracing. The release was immediate. The release impacted the trailer floor. A cleanup contractor was dispatched to clean up the release. The damaged bags were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum and the recovered material and cleanup debris were placed into a separate 55-gallon poly drum.

This incident pertains to a release of a UN1090 Acetone. Approximately half of a gallon released from (1) - 1 gallon metal paint can due to the can falling over during transit and the lid was damaged. The release impacted a small part of the trailer floor. The release duration was overtime during transit. Terminal personnel donned correct PPE and conducted cleanup operations.

column168: On 10/21/15 the customer, Aspen Aerogels loaded 60 drums into a Clean Harbors van trailer. During transit shortly after leaving the customer site the Clean Harbors driver notices something leaking from the van trailer. The driver immediately pulled over onto a side street.  The driver then started deploying speedi-dri, and sorbent boom around the spill area. Both the local Fire Dept and Clean Harbors Response Team were notified and responded. It was determined that a metal drum was punctured during loading operations.  The damaged drum was over packed and the spill area was cleaned up using additional sorbent material. The over pack and clean up material were sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: The customer was advise to have their forklift employees take more caution when loading containers into van trailer.

column168: Barstow, CA Mechanical Foreman noted that car NATX 29781 was discovered having a commodity release by BNSF Mechanical Carmen on track 1507 at 1045-CT.  The estimated release to the ground was 1 to 2 cups.  BNSF Mechanical attempted to secure bottom outlet valve handle with no movement.  Bottom outlet cap was loosened and thread tape was reapplied to secure release.  Car was bad ordered due to defective bottom outlet valve pending OTMA.
column169: Forward this information to those in charge of unloading, maintenance, securement and pre-trip inspections so they can review their procedures to prevent this from occurring in the future.

column168: BMOU 204729 intermodal container was found in the Haslet, TX intermodal yard leaking product from the container.  Upon inspection it was found that a 275 gallon tote was crushed from improper loading and securement.  The 275 gallon tote was punctured by the improper securement and loading allowing five gallons of product to be released.  BNSF responders off loaded BMOU 204729 container, transferred the product from the damaged tote and neutralized the contaminated container.  BMOU 204729 was properly reloaded and processed for further shipment.

column168: Reported that (1) 500 gallon tote of UN2672 Class 8 PG III was arrived leaking inside of trailer #0A2570. The cause of the release was a loose cap on the top of the tote. The venting bung cap was then safely secured on top of the tote. No soils, waterways, or drains were reported to have been impacted by the release.

column168: The TOBOV was not fully closed and leaked into the secondary closure (bottom outlet nozzle).  Upon further investigation it was discovered that one of the 4 bolts securing the bottom outlet nozzle, below the valve had broken, allowing release of the product . column168: This incident pertains to a release of a UN3145 Corrosive Liquid Alky-phenols. Approximately 5 gallons released from (1) - 330 gallon poly tote due to the tote being damaged by other freight on the trailer during transit. The release impacted a small portion of the dock and trailer floor. An Environmental Service contractor was dispatched to contain, cleanup, and transfer the release.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Truck/trailer was traveling west on US 290 Hwy service road west bound making a left turn at the intersection of US 183 service road south bound. Driver took the turn to fast causing the load to shift in the trailer. The driver lost control of the truck/trailer and rolled it over on its right side. An approximate 3 inch gash in the trailer resulted in the roll over releasing product. The tanker was hauling 8,000 gallons of gasoline and all was recovered except 660 gallons that was discharged into a storm drain. All recovered product was pumped into an empty trailer or removed with a vacuum truck. All products on the roadway were absorbed with oil dri. The storm inlet was flushed with 2,500 gallons of water.
column169: Driver was terminated from duty and additional training on rollovers has and will continue to be presented to all Sun Coast drivers.

Con-Way personnel cleaned the released material using absorbents. The damaged 5 gallon jug, and all absorbent materials used were put into a 10 gallon over pack and placed into OS&D. No waterways, soils, or storm drains were reported to have been impacted by the release.

column168: Please be advised that LAN Cargo, S.A. received a transferred shipment from Amerijet International Inc. on October 2, 2015 under AWB No.  810-45183235.   Amerijet International, Inc. reported to LAN Cargo, S.A. that the referenced shipment consisted of 1 fiberboard box and was declared as a non-dangerous good cargo.    LAN Cargo transported the referenced non-dangerous good cargo to Lima, Peru on flight UC 1407 on October 4, 2015 .     However, LAN Cargo, S.A. detected in Lima, Peru that the referenced Amerijet International, Inc. shipment also contained dangerous goods UN3263 Corrosive solid basic, organic, and UN 3077 environmentally hazardous substance, solid which were not properly reported to LAN Cargo, S.A.

column168: Quality Transport driver was getting ready to unload some fresh caustic into fresh caustic Tank-274.  He hooked up the hose to the tank offloading line.  He then opened up the tanker’s internal hydraulic valve.  He then removed the end cap to the outlet of the tanker without noticing that the manual valve was open.  When he removed the end cap, caustic started blowing out and hitting him on the chest. . He then moved to the side and closed the hydraulic internal valve. A approximately 80-gallons of caustic was released under pressure. The Western operator showed the driver to the safety shower where he rinsed off himself for fifteen minutes.       While the Kurtz responders were taking the driver to the nurses station, it was noticed that the Western operator’s neck was showing irritation signs where he had gotten sprayed with caustic. The operator was taken to the change room where he showered and was also taken to the nurse’s station.
column169: Re-emphasize the importance of following guidelines for following and understanding proper unloading procedures.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: reported that the driver was moving a pallet of roach spray inside of trailer #LE003 at 104 New Era Drive South Plainfield, NJ 07080 when he noticed a pile of unknown grey powder on the floor of trailer #LE003. column168: CN Mechanical Department employee noted liquid coming from tank car UTLX 299064(Load, Ethanol and Gasoline mixture, UN 3475) during an inspection at the CN Kirk Yard, Gary, Indiana. column168: On 10/22/15, the TILX 257227 was found in Barstow track 1202 with approximately 1/2 gallon of asphalt on the side of the car which had leaked from the manway area.  BNSF Hazmat responders inspected the car and found the manway lid gasket was cracked and no longer able to seal the car.  Responders replaced the gasket and resecured the car.  Asphalt was wiped from the side of the car and the car was released to destination.  Release amounts are estimated based upon observations by the responding personnel.
column169: Follow up with shipper (Holly Frontier) to identify the root cause of the incident.  Holly Frontier should ensure loading personnel are properly trained on loading and inspection procedures to ensure that cars are secured and will not leak while in transportation to consignee facility.

The resulting derailment punctured the XOMX 100512 on the B end/left side of the car.  The spill of asphalt was contained to the BNSF ROW.  The slow released was stopped when the car was uprighted at approximately 17:00 on 10/23/15.  The cooled and solidified asphalt was excavated from the ROW and placed into containment with plastic containment underneath and over the soil.  Release amounts are estimated based upon visual observations.

column168: During unloading operations, one 5 gallon drum of UN2735 Polyamines was punctured via forklift resulting in an estimated 4.5 liquid gallons of material to be released to the trailer floor. Onsite personnel conducted cleanup activities. The damaged drum and waste debris has been placed into a drum and staged onsite pending disposition. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: While unloading freight material handler discovered a drum that was slightly leaking from the bottom chime. A pallet that was used as dunnage to secure the drum had be pushed into the drum consequently puncturing it and contributing to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container as was the punctured drum.
column169: Make sure the dunnage used is secure as well to prevent these types of unintentional events.

column168: While unloading freight from trailer forklift operator misjudged the clearances of his fork blades and punctured two pails that were staged on a pallet. The two punctured pails were removed, spilled material cleaned with absorbent and placed in to a recovery container as were the damaged pails.
column169: Forklift operators need to pay attention to the clearances of the forklift they are operating including the forkblades.

column168: While loading freight into trailer forklift operator hit a pail on a pallet that was already staged in the trailer with the blade of his forklift consequently puncturing it and contributing to the unintentional release. column169: Forklift operators need to pay attention to the clearances of their forkblades to prevent these type of events from occurring.

A tanker offloading Diesel Fuel UN1993 into a UST at a TA truck stop in Baytown, TX overfilled a vent line and released the fuel onto the parking lot and soil ditch line. Approximately 200 gallons of UN1993 Diesel fuel overfilled from the tanker during unloading operations as the result of human error. Contractors were dispatched with a vacuum truck to remove as much of the product as possible into a frac tank and vac truck. The contaminated soil was excavated and is being monitored daily due to high rain levels.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: AEROSOLS, NON-FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: Undeclared hazmat was found during screening. Local FAA hazmat agents were notified.

While performing a routine site inspection of the Veolia facility located in Port Washington, WI, a Veolia employee noticed a small leak from a van trailer. Upon further investigation, the spill was discovered to be coming from a drum of flammable solvents that had developed two pin sized holes on the side. The holes were located approximately one and eight inches from the top of the drum. Veolia employees contained the spill, placed the drum into a salvage drum, and absorbed all free liquid. All clean-up material was then placed into the salvage drum.
column169: The incident was reviewed with Veolia field personnel with an emphasis on ensuring that a thorough review of container integrity is performed prior to transporting a container of hazardous material. In this scenario, it would have been very difficult to detect the holes on the side of the drum as they were extremely small.

column168: A transformer containing PCB oil >500ppm was received at the Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. transfer facility at Kent, WA. During the unloading process an employee grasped a protruding valve to slide the transformer causing the valve to break off and release residual material from within the valve. An in house clean-up crew was summoned, donned the proper PPE, and remediated the impacted concrete of the warehouse floor. The generated clean up waste was properly packaged and disposed of together with the leaking transformer at the original disposal destination. The Washington State Department of Ecology was notified. WDEQ operator Colleen provided report #ERTS-660235.
column169: At the time the transformer/container was accepted for shipment no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. In order to prevent a recurrence the driver has been retrained on container inspection and advised to reject any containers without valves removed or drained prior to being offered for transportation. Facility personnel have been counseled and received retraining on the proper handling of transformers both drained and containing liquid waste.

column168: A roll-off truck and trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. was loading an intermodal roll-off container at a Clean Harbors facility at Clive, UT. During the course of loading the contents shifted and flowed over the rear of the roll-off container and spilled onto the ground. The driver immediately  stopped the loading procedure. The roll-off container was then placed back onto the ground. The driver notified his immediate supervisor. A cleanup  crew was summoned, donned the proper PPE and the released material was placed back into the roll-off container and the roll off was secured. The  roll-off was then reloaded onto the truck without incident and delivered to the final disposal destination. Utah DEQ provides report # 12410.
column169: The shipper was notified of the intermodal roll-off containing excess free liquids and advised of the proper loading parameters for the container  involved. The shipper has also been advised to inspect all outbound containers for excess free liquid. The driver had been previously advised to inspect the load  condition for overloading, uneven loading or excess free liquids prior to loading any roll-off container and reject containers that have been loaded  improperly. This was the second occurrence of identical nature for this driver. The previous occurrence took place on 10/8/2015 resulting in a hazardous release. The driver has been terminated for cause. The inbound Clean Harbors transfer facility has also been advised to inspect all inbound intermodal containers for proper loading conditions prior to releasing them for further transportation.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING, SINGLE VEHICLE ACCIDENT RESULTED IN A ROLLOVER. FREIGHT WAS DAMAGED INSIDE TRAILER AND ENGINE RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF MOTOR OIL TO THE ROAD SHOULDER. ILLINOIS DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, LOGAN COUNTY EMA, LINCOLN FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND ILLINOIS STATE POLICE RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE.  LINCOLN FIRE DEPARTMENT ASSISTED IN OFFLOAD OF THE DAMAGED FREIGHT TO ACCESS THE LEAKING DRUMS, AND APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE RELEASED MOTORS OIL ON THE ROAD SHOULDER. SITE WAS SECURE PENDING CONTRACTOR RESPONSE. SUNPRO, INC WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON INSPECTION, EIGHT (8) 55-GALLON DRUMS OF POLYMERS (NON-RESTRICTED INK, PRINTERS) WERE DISCOVERED DAMAGED INSIDE TRAILER. SUNPRO INC. APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE FREE PRODUCT INSIDE TRAILER, AND BEGAN TO PUMP REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED DRUMS. AS DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS EMPTIED, SUNPRO INC PROCEEDED TO RECOVER THE SPENT ABSORBENTS FROM THE ROAD SHOULDER, AND HAND EXCAVATED THE IMPACTED SOILS ALONG THE SHOULDER. APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF POLYMERS RELEASED INSIDE THE TRAILER, APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF POLYMERS RELEASED TO SOIL BENEATH TRAILER, AND APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF MOTOR OIL RELEASED TO THE ROAD SHOULDER. SUNPRO INC, RECOVERED ALL DAMAGED FREIGHT, FREE PRODUCT, SPENT ABSORBENTS, AND DEBRIS, WHICH WERE TRANSPORTED OFF SITE, PENDING DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: ROADRUNNER TRANSPORTATION SERVICES, INC. WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: During the loading process a Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. driver attempted to clear, remove and cap the hose at the completion of loading. While stowing the capped hose in the hose tray of the trailer the driver lost control of the hose causing it to become dislodged at the trailer loading valve. The resulting hose disconnection caused approximately a 30 gallon release of material from within the hose. Dispatch was notified and an in house response crew was summoned. The response crew donned the proper PPE and cleaned the released material. The associated clean up materials were containerized and disposed of properly. The Utah Department of Environmental Quality was notified. Duty operator Morgan provided report #12414.
column169: An internal investigation was conducted and it was determined that the cause of the release was directly related to the failure of the driver to fully clear and control the hose at the conclusion of the loading process. The driver was counselled and retrained on operational procedures relating to vacuum tanker loading / unloading. The driver was disciplined per company policy for a preventable incident.

On 10/29/15 at 1834 hours it was reported in the CSXT Gentilly Yard located in New Orleans, LA, discovered UTLX660826, a residue tank car of Environmentally Hazardous Substances, N.O.S. (Petroleum Oils) to be leaking from the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, Warren Distribution, was notified. United States Environmental Services, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and secured the leak.  It was discovered that the bottom outlet valve was left partially open.  USES closed the valve.  It was also discovered that 7 of the 8 manway securement bolts were left hanging and the remaining bolt was left less than tool tight.  The protective housing pin was not engaged and the liquid line plug was less than tool tight. These actions were communicated to the shipper. The car was secured, re-sealed, and all product on the ground was excavated and placed in drums for disposal. This incident did not require a special switching move.    NAR Cause Code: 148  Bottom Outlet Valve  Less than tool tight, valve open    5(5+4+1) x (2+0) = 100 NARRI         New Orleans, LA  10/29/15  UTLX660826  Environmentally Hazardous Substances, N.O.S. (Petroleum Oils)
column169: The shipper should ensure a proper outbound inspection is conducted prior to offering/ releasing a car for transportation.

column168: On Wednesday, 14 October 15’ at approximately 11:40AM Waterline Tech arrived to JCI Torrance for a Sodium Hypochlorite Will Call order. JCI Plant worker was loading Waterline Tech’s 3 Axle Straight-truck with 1250g tank and 1 ea. 550g mega tote combination unit, starting with 1250g tank. JCI plant worker finished filling 1250g tank at approx. 11:58AM. JCI plant worker was giving instruction to move so that driver could re-position truck to second tank (mega tote), was at that moment the movement from truck caused bleach to surge out from the top of 1250g tank because lid was not shut. 2 ½ gallons of bleach was spilled onto pavement near loading rack. Bleach spill was promptly picked up using spill kit by JCI employees.
column169: This incident could have been prevented had the driver and loader taken the precautions and communicated to confirm that tanker lid was properly closed before moving truck forward to fill mega tote tank.

column168: At 10:52 pm Asphalt U.O was notified by Baseline Logistics’ driver that his tanker was leaking.  The driver had finished loading 150 barrels of asphalt product.  Once he completed the load he made a walk around his rig this is when he noticed a drip that immediately grew into a leak.  The U.O contacted the Shift Supervisor and the Security which in turn called out Kurtz to the scene.  A Level 2 was called out and on site ERT came out to be on standby should the spill got out of hand. The Asphalt and Vac truck operators found a way to unload the leaking tanker back into a product tank, by doing this 75 barrels that would have ended up in the trench were recovered.
column169: Emphasize the importance with the trucking company for safe loading practices and work with them on verification on their vehicle integrity tests as required. Since we are the loading facility we will work with Baseline to ensure this does not happen again.

column168: At 0955 EST it was reported that there was a 1-cup release of UN1993 to the dock floor at the Con-Way Freight terminal in Dallas TX. The release of the material was the result of a 1-gallon jug becoming forked by a forklift, causing an immediate release. Terminal personnel performed mitigation of the site, placing the impacted materials, PPE and damaged jug into a 10-gallon overpack. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The site was returned to previous condition.

The driver of the Crossett tanker overfilled the tank during unloading operations at the consignee location. Approximately 1,600 gallons of NA1993 Diesel fuel was estimated to have been overfilled into the concrete containment pit surrounding the tank. There was no impact to the environment, drains, or waterways. An environmental contractor responded to conduct clean-up of the pit and remove the free-standing fuel for disposal. The site was restored to its original condition.

Product was being unloaded from tank truck to storage tank. There is a secondary line that runs to the railcar unloading station. The shut off valve at the railcar unloading station was not closed all the way. Product leaked through the dust cover on the inlet. This was not discovered until the unloading was finished. Onsite Storm drain was pumped out along with ditch just outside fence. Outside contractor was called in to dig up impacted soil.
column169: Employees retrained to make sure all valves are closed before unloading any products. The unloading line that was used to off load the product did not have a shut off valve at the tank truck scale, only at the railcar unloading station which is on the other side of the building. Unloading Procedure has been changed to use a different unloading line that has a shut off valve to railcar station at the tank truck unloading area.

column168: During loading activities, two 1 quart cans of UN1263 Paint were crushed by other freight resulting in an estimated 1 liquid quart to be released to the trailer floor. Onsite personnel conducted clean up and placed the damaged cans and impacted absorbents into a waste drum to be staged onsite pending disposition instructions from the shipper. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted.

Approximately 1 pint of UN1866 Resin solution released from a 55 gallon drum that was punctured by a forklift during offloading activities. The release impacted the trailer floor and was confined to the inside of the trailer. A contractor responded and cleaned the impacted area with absorbents. The damaged drum was over packed. The impacted absorbents were collected and containerized for disposal.

AT about 8:00 P.M. Shift Supervisor was called by security that the loaders were trying to contact Armando Arrieta to go to the middle rack and meet with them. Upon reaching the rack Armando met with Eugene Martinez, Isaac Cardenas and a contractor Francisco Lopez.  They explained to Armando that as they were loading the last two cars as one was about to get full they open up the last car and let it fill as they button up the car that just got full. They didn’t realize that the last car was close to getting full itself.  It was Francisco Lopez that first noticed the over fill and let the loaders know what was happening; they closed the valves quickly to prevent more products from spilling. Armando guessed it was about 1 bbl of product on the ground from what Armando could see. Armando notified T. Weick of the situation and he said he would have it cleaned up in the morning. Security was notified not to let the UP remove that car, also Wes Waida was notified of the spill. The product was Fuel Oil from T-118, and the RR car was UTLX677800.

column168: Vehicle No. 1 (Brenner CTMV) struck Vehicle No. 2 (a flat-bed semi-trailer) which was parked in the northbound travel lane (facing south and loaded with building products). Vehicle No. 2 had no warning devices displayed. The front headboard and frame of Vehicle No. 2 ripped the front compartment on Vehicle No. 1 open, releasing 4,000 gallons of no lead gasoline onto the roadway. The release was immediate. Au Gres-Sims-Whitney Fire Department responded and put down absorbent material. Northern A-1 Services was contracted for the initial response and remediation services.    The total property damage, response costs and remediation costs are not yet available.

column168: A TRACTOR-TRAILER CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 172 BARRELS (7200 GALLONS) OF CRUDE OIL WAS ATTEMPTING A SHARP RIGHT TURN ON NICKELS MICA ROAD TO CROSS RAILROAD TRACKS, WHEN RIGHT SIDE TRAILER WHEELS LEFT THE ROAD INTO DITCH AND TURNED TRACTOR AND TRAILER ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE, BLOCKING THE RAILROAD TRACKS. UPRC TRAIN WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON TRACKS WHEN THE TRAIN ENGINEER NOTICED TRUCK AND TRAILER BLOCKING TRACKS AND APPLIED EMERGENCY BRAKES. TRAIN WAS ALMOST COMPLETELY STOPPED AT TIME OF CONTACT WITH TRAILER. COLLISION UPRIGHTED TRUCK TRACTOR AND MOVED TRUCK AND TRAILER APPROXIMATELY 20-30 FEET BEFORE COMING TO COMPLETE STOP. COLLISION CAUSED RUPTURE IN TOP-FORWARD PORTION OF TRAILER (STILL RESTING ON ITS RIGHT SIDE) CAUSING CARGO TO SPILL ONTO THE RAILROAD TRACKS AND NICKEL ROAD. UPRC MANAGED ENTIRE CLEAN-UP OPERATION.

column168: THE CRYOGENIC TRANSPORT, LLC UNIT WAS TRAVELING ON THE EXIT/ENTRANCE RAMP OF I-45 SOUTHBOUND ONTO I 610 EASTBOUND NEAR HOUSTON, TEXAS. THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE UNIT AND WENT OFF THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY AND OVERTURNED. THE TANK ON THE TRAILER WAS DAMAGED AND APPROXIMATELY 8640 GALLONS OF LIQUID HELIUM WAS ABLE TO ESCAPE INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. A LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR RESPONDED TO THE SCENE BUT NO REMEDIATION FROM THE CARGO RELEASE WAS NECESSARY. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: CYROGENIC TRANSPORT, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE DRIVING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: AT 17:35 ON THURSDAY, OCTOBER 29, 2015, AN EMPLOYEE WORKING IN THE AREA OBSERVED A PACKAGE TRAVELING ON A CONVEYOR BELT WHICH HAD FLAMES COMING FROM INSIDE A FIBERBOARD BOX BEARING A ZEP LOGO.  THE EMPLOYEE STOPPED THE CONVEYOR BELT AND COMMUNICATED THE SITUATION TO A MANAGEMENT EMPLOYEE.  AN EVACUATION OF THE FACILITY TOOK PLACE AND THE ONTARIO FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED AS THE FIRE SUPPRESSION SYSTEM (SPRINKLER SYSTEM) WAS TRIGGERED.  AT 18:30, AFTER ALMOST 90 MINUTES OF EVACUATION, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ALLOWED EMPLOYEES TO RETURN INSIDE THE BUILDING.  THE SOURCE PACKAGE AND OTHERS AROUND IT WERE DAMAGED OR DESTROYED IN THE FIRE MAKING IT DIFFICULT TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE PACKAGE FAILURE.  INTERVIEWS, PHOTOGRAPHS OF THE DEBRIS, AND PACKAGE TRACKING INFORMATION FROM THE REST OF THE SHIPMENT INDICATE THAT THE SOURCE PACKAGE CONTAINED TWELVE 32 OZ PLASTIC BOTTLES OF ZEB BRAND KLEAR WINDSHIELD WASHER CONCENTRATE CLEANER.  A SEPARATE 5800.1 FORM IS BEING SUBMITTED FOR SOME DAMAGED AEROSOL CANS THAT WERE FOUND AMOUNT THE DEBRIS FROM AN UNIDENTIFIED PACKAGE.    MULTIPLE #1    THE FIRE-DAMAGED AEROSOL CANS IN REPORT I-2015110715 SEE ATTACHMENTS) WERE COLLATERAL DAMAGE DISCOVERED IN THE DEBRIS FROM A PACKAGE FIRE THAT OCCURRED AT 17:35 ON THURSDAY, OCTOBER 29, 2015.  A SEPARATE 5800.1 FORM HAS BEEN SUBMITTED FOR THE SOURCE PACKAGE OF THE FIRE.  SEE NRC REPORT NUMBER 1132578.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE CANS THEMSELVES AND THE OUTER PACKAGING WAS NOT IDENTIFIABLE IN THE DEBRIS.
column169: UNABLE TO DETERMINE EXACT CAUSE OF FAILURE TO DEVELOP FUTURE PREVENTATIVE MEASURES.

column168: Vehicle was traveling east bound on 1-70 near mile marker 65, when driver lost control and ran off the roadway.Vehicle rolled over onto its passenger side. Driver stated that the vehicle all at once started to pull hard to the right,driver tried to regain control but was unable to do so. Vehicle came to rest on its passenger side and began leakingproduct on the ground. The steering arm was found broken.Summit Environmental was called out to the scene, by OMI Environmental on behalf of Service Transport Company.Summit found product leaking from around the washout nipple; they put a patch around the nipple to help stop theleak. Product leaked about 10 hours at a fast drip.
column169: Service Transport Company has checked the entire fleet for faulty steering arms and replaced those arms that didnot have a Zirt fitting from the manufacturer.

column168: WHILE IN THE PROCESS OF LOADING WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID FROM GENERATOR’S TANK THROUGH A THREE INCH TRANSFER HOSE INTO THE TRANSPORTER’S CARGO TANK, THE GENERATOR/LOADER WAS CONTROLLING THE DISCHARGE VALVE AND THE PUMP OPERATION ON THEIR END.     AT THE SAME TIME, THE TRANSPORTER OPERATING THE VACUUM UNIT ATTACHED TO HIS CARGO TANK, BUILT UP ENOUGH VACUUM AND OPENED THE PRIMARY AND SECONDARY CONTAINMENT VALVES AT THE REAR END OF HIS TRAILER, TO FACILITATE THE TRANSFER OF THE WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID IN TO THE CARGO TANK THROUGH THE TRANSFER HOSE.     UPON THE GENERATOR/LOADER EMPTYING THE GENERATOR TANK, THE LOADER CLOSED THE DISCHARGE VALVES ON THE GENERATORS TANK AND SHUT DOWN THE PUMP. THE LOADER SIGNALED THE DRIVER THAT THE TANK WAS EMPTY. THE TRANSPORTER THEN ALLOWED THE VACUUM PUMP TO OPERATE FOR APPROXIMATELY SIXTY SECONDS OR ENOUGH TIME TO CLEAR TRANSFER HOSE OF ANY PRODUCT OR RESIDUE. THE TRANSPORTER THEN CLOSED THE PRIMARY AND SECONDARY CONTAINMENT VALVES AND SHUT DOWN THE VACUUM PUMP.     THE TRANSPORTER THEN CONFIRMED THAT THE TRANSFER HOSE WAS EMPTY BY LIFTING THE HOSE TO CONFIRM THAT THERE WAS NO WEIGHT FROM THE PRODUCT OR RESIDUE REMAINING IN THE HOUSE. HE THEN CAREFULLY BROKE THE TRANSFER HOSE CONNECTION FITTING FROM THE GENERATOR’S DISCHARGE PIPE FITTING TO CONFIRM THAT THERE WAS NO REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE TRANSFER HOUSE.     UPON BREAKING THE CONNECTION AT THE GENERATOR’S DISCHARGE FITTING, THE TRANSPORTER/DRIVER OBSERVED THE PRODUCT SPILLING OUT OF THE HOSE AND IMMEDIATELY DROPPED THE HOSE INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA GROUND SURFACE GROUND TO AVOID GETTING SPLASHED. TWENTY GALLONS OF ADDITIONAL PRODUCT OR RESIDUE ESCAPED ON TO THE CONTAINMENT AREA FLOOR OR SURFACE.
column169: CHANGES THAT HAVE TAKEN PLACE AS A RESULT OF THE SPILL INCLUDE; TRANSPORTERS ARE REQUIRED TO USE AN ADAPTER FITTING BETWEEN THE HOSE CONNECTOR FITTING AND THE GENERATOR’S DISCHARGE PIPER FITTING. THIS ADAPTER FITTING IS INCORPORATED WITH A ONE INCH SHUT OFF VALVE THAT IS TO BE OPENED PRIOR TO THE TRANSPORTER/DRIVER SHUTTING OFF THE VACUUM PUMP. OPERATION OR OPENING OF THIS ONE INCH SHUT OFF VALVE WHILE UNDER VACUUM ALLOWS AIR TO ENTER THE TRANSFER HOSE WHILE IT IS UNDER THE VACUUM, WHICH THEREBY CLEARS THE HOSE OF ANY REMAINING PRODUCT OR RESIDUE.     THE GENERATOR IS REQUIRED TO USE AN ELEVATED TRANSFER HOSE SUPPORT STAND THAT ELEVATES THE TRANSFER HOSE SEVERAL FEET FROM THE GROUND. THIS MINIMIZES THE POSSIBILITY OF THE REMAINING PRODUCT OR RESIDUE IN THE TRANSFER HOSE FROM ESCAPING.     AFTER INTERVIEWING THE DRIVER, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE IS A PROBABILITY THAT THE DRIVER DID NOT ASCERTAIN THAT THE TRANSFER HOSE WAS CLEAR OF ANY REMAINING PRODUCT OR RESIDUE PRIOR TO BREAKING THE TRANSFER HOSE CONNECTION AT THE GENERATOR’S DISCHARGE PIPE. A DECISION HAS BEEN MADE TO RETRAIN OUR DRIVER IN THE OPERATION OF A VACUUM TRAILER WITH RESPECT TO THE ASSOCIATED RISKS RELATIVE TO THE ENVIRONMENT AND SAFETY CONCERNS FOR BOTH THE DRIVER AND THE GENERATOR PERSONNEL. THE DRIVER IS NOT PERMITTED BACK ON THIS SITE UNTIL ADEQUATE, AND ADDITIONAL TRAINING HAS BEEN COMPLETED.     AS THE RESULT OF ANY UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND HM-183 CARGO TANK INSPECTION AND TESTING REQUIREMENTS, THE CARRIER HAS REGISTERED THROUGH U.S DOT/FMCSA TO ENGAGE IN THE INSPECTION AND TESTING OF CARGO TANKS. THE CARRIER HAS CONDUCTED AND COMPLETED A POST-INCIDENT INVESTIGATION AND INSPECTION OF OUR CARGO TANK, INCLUDING VACUUM TESTING OF THE EXTERNAL/INTERNAL VALVES OR CAPS, VACUUM VENTS/AIR GAUGE AND DATA DISKS. THE RESULTS OF THIS INSPECTION HAS CONCLUDED THAT WHILE UNDER VACUUM DURING THE INSPECTION PROCESS THAT THE EXTERNAL AND INTERNAL VALVES HELD VACUUM FOR TWENTY MINUTES. DURING THIS PERIOD IN TIME, THE CARGO TANK VACUUM GAUGE INDICATED NO VARIATION OR DEVIATION WHEN COMPARED WITH OUR EXTERNAL VACUUM PUMP AND GAUGE THAT IS USED FOR LEAK TESTING.

column168: THE STAR TANKER WAS PARKED ON THE NEW WALMART PARKING LOT UNLOADING THE ONLY COMPARTMENT OF DIESEL FUEL THEY HAD. THE VAPOR RECOVERY VENT WAS HOOKED UP FIRST AND FROM THE VERY START OF THE PROCESS, FUEL WAS NOT ENTERING THE UNDERGROUND DIESEL TANK. WITH THE DROP HOSE FULL AND PRESSURE ON IT TOO. THE DRIVER CLOSED THE BELLY VALVES AND WAITED TO ALLOW PRESSURE TO GO DOWN EVEN THOUGH THE DIESEL TANK WAS NOT FULL. IT WOULD NOT. IN AN ATTEMPT TO DISCONNECT FROM THE DROP TUBE, AN ESTIMATED 25 GALLONS OF DIESEL WAS RELEASED INTO THE BUCKET FIRST AND THEN TO THE CONCRETE. THE DRIVER USED PADS TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. NO DIESEL REACHED ANY WATER OR MANWAY. AFTER CONTAINING THE SPILL. THE DRIVER CALLED DISPATCH FOR HELP. THE FIRE DEPT CAME TO THE SCENE AND STAR CALLED TAS ENVIRONMENTAL TO REMOVE AND CLEAN THE CONCRETE SITE. USING THE DIFFERENT FITTING WITH VAPOR BYPASS. THE COMPARTMENT WAS UNLOADED BEFORE LEAVING. A REPAIR TRUCK CALLED BY THE STORE MANAGER, ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND WORKED ON THE NO LEAD AND DIESEL VENTING SYSTEMS, THE NEXT LOAD OF DIESEL TO THAT SITE UNLOADED SMOOTHLY. ALL LIQUID AND SOLIDS WERE PLACED IN TWO 55 GALLON DRUMS AND REMOVE TO THE WILSON COUNTY LANDFILL, MICROBES AND OIL-DRY WERE USED TO CLEAN UP CONCRETE .

column168: OUR DRIVER TIM PLYLER HAD SPENT SATURDAY NIGHT AT THE PETRO TRUCK-STOP IN KINGMAN AZ. AFTER PARKING, A WALK AROUND INSPECTION OF THE TRUCK AND TRAILER SHOWED NO LEAKS OR NOTHING OUT OF THE ORDINARY. WHEN MR. PLYLER GETS UP AT APPROXIMATELY 0800 ON SUNDAY MORNING AND EXITS THE TRUCK, HE NOTICES A SMELL. HE THEN WALKS TO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AND SEES EVIDENCE THAT A LEAK HAD DEVELOPED INSIDE THE TRAILER. HE OPENS THE DOOR AND SEES THE LEAK IS COMING FROM THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. HE CALLS HIS DISPATCHER AND REPORTS THAT HE HAS A LEAK. THE DISPATCHER TELLS MR. PLYLER TO CALL THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER ON THE MANIFEST.     THE NUMBER WAS CALLED AND A RESPONSE CRE (H20) ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 1530. THE CREW BEGAN TAKING PALLETS OF MATERIAL OFF THE TRAILER IN SEARCH OF THE LEAKING DRUM. A POLY DRUM WAS FOUND IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER THAT HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A NAIL PROTRUDING UPWARD FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE PALLET. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVER-PACKED. AFTER INSPECTION OF THE REST OF THE LOAD IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE ONE DRUM WAS THE ONLY ONE LEAKING. AT THAT POINT EVERYTHING WAS CLEANED OFF WIPED DOWN AND RE-LOADED ONTO THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER AND LOAD WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE AT APPROXIMATELY 2345.
column169: IN THIS PARTICULAR EVENT THE PROBLEM WAS THAT A NAIL HAD BECOME DISLODGED FROM THE WOOD IN THE PALLET. AND THRU THE VIBRATIONS CREATED BY THE MOTION OF TRANSIT PUNCTURED A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF A POLY DRUM. A CLOSER INSPECT OF THE PALLETS FOR LOOSE OR MIS-DRIVEN NAILS COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS OCCURRENCE.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On Friday October 16, 2015, Santa received an order from its customer BC Exchange to fill the subject tank.  Upon arrival the morning of Monday October 19, 2015, Santa’s driver was met by a BC Exchange building maintenance employee who identified and unlocked the tank’s covered fill pipe on the sidewalk next to the 36 Center Street entrance of BC Exchange’s building.When asked by the Santa driver if the tank level was low enough to accept a full delivery from the Santa truck, the BC Exchange employee indicated that he had taken a tank level reading on the prior Friday and confirmed that the tank level was low and should be filled with the full load.  To double-check the tank level during filling, the Santa driver relied on the vent whistle located on the wall adjacent to the fill pipe.  While delivering the full 3,259 gallon load of product, the Santa driver continued to hear the confirmatory whistle (indicating remaining capacity in the tank) and observed no odors or other indications of an overfill at his location, outside the building.     After the Santa driver completed this delivery and left the site, BC Exchange employees reported they smelled oil and went into the lower parking garage to investigate, where the maintenance employee found oil coming from under the door to the room where the tank is located and entering a drain outside this utility room.  The BC Exchange Place employee called the Waterbury Fire Department, as well as Santa.  Santa called CTR, a CTDEEP-licensed spill contractor, to assist with the response to the incident. Upon further investigation, it was determined that the fuel oil product came out the pressure relief valve on the top of the tank in the utility room of the building’s lower parking garage. The relief valve and vent whistle do not appear to have operated correctly as they allowed product overflow from the relief valve with no indication of the tank’s full status at the location of the fill and vent pipes and vent whistle, where the driver would have been alerted.  The investigations also determined that the oil entering the garage drain flowed into a concrete catch basin and associated sump pump system connected to the municipal storm sewer.  The sump pump system in BC Exchange’s building is believed to activate automatically.  The storm sewers drain from Center Street to Bank and South Main Streets, into the underground culvert that flows to the outfall on the banks of the Naugatuck River.
column169: On all future deliveries both the driver and the building maintenance personnel will verify the tank level prior to delivery. It was also recommended that an audible and visual high level alarm be installed on the tank in the fill area.

column168: A ROLLOVER ACCIDENT INVOLVING A TRACTOR TRAILER ALONG A TWO-LANE STATE ROUTE CAUSED EMERGENCY RESPONDERS TO CLOSE THE STATE ROUTE WHEN A DOT4L - 200 CRYOGENIC LIQUID CYLINDER RELEASED PRODUCT THROUGH ITS PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE.     THERE WAS NO FAILURE OF THE PACKAGE AND THE RELEASE OF NITROGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, WAS VENTED THROUGH THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE WHEN THE OVERTURNING OF THE VEHICLE CAUSED THE LIQUID NITROGEN IN THE CYLINDER TO SUBMERGE THE INLET TO THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. THE NITROGEN CYLINDER AS WELL AS OTHER CYLINDERS REMAINED SECURED TO THE VEHICLE BUT THE ORIENTATION CHANGED AS A RESULT OF THE VEHICLE OVERTURNING. THE FIRST RESPONDERS TO THE SCENE OF THE INCIDENT INITIALLY REPORTED THE PACKAGE WAS DAMAGED AND LEAKING AND CLOSED THE HIGHWAY AS A RESULT. PRAXAIR'S INTERNAL RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED AT THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT, COMPLETED AN INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE, AND EXPLAINED TO THE FIRST RESPONDERS THAT THE PACKAGE DID NOT FAIL AND WAS NOT DAMAGED. INSTEAD, IT WAS VENTING THROUGH THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE AS DESIGNED TO PREVENT THE BUILDUP OF INTERNAL PRESSURE THAT COULD CAUSE FAILURE OF THE PACKAGING.

column168: ON OCTOBER 22, OUR DRIVER PICKED UP A LOAD OF TERGITOL NP-9 SURFACTANT AT UNION CARBIDE/OIL TANKING IN TEXAS CITY, TEXAS. THE DRIVER LEFT THE FACILITY AND PROCEEDED TO HIS DELIVERY POINT IN HOUSTON, TEXAS. WHEN HE ARRIVED OUTSIDE OF THE CUSTOMER THAT HE WAS SCHEDULED TO DELIVER TO HE LOOKED IN HIS MIRROR AND NOTICED THAT THERE WAS PRODUCT DRIPPING DOWN THE SIDE OF HIS TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY GOT OUT AND ACCESSED THE SITUATION AND DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE WASHOUT CAPS ON TOP OF THE TRAILER WAS LOOSE. HE TIGHTENED THE WASH OUT CAP THAT WAS ON TOP OF THE TRAILER AND STOPPED THE LEAK. HE THEN WIPED OFF THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND MADE HIS DELIVERY.    IT IS ESTIMATED THAT ABOUT 3 TO 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER. PLEASE NOT THAT THE PRODUCT ONLY LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER AS THE PRODUCT WAS SLOSHING AROUND AND NOT THE ENTIRE TIME THAT HE WAS DRIVING.
column169: IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE DRIVER COMPLETED HIS DELIVERY BOTH HE AND THE TRAILER RETURNED BACK TO THE TERMINAL. THE DRIVER WAS INTERVIEWED BY HIS SAFETY MANAGER AND THE MAINTENANCE DEPARTMENT INSPECTED THE TRAILER.     LANGER TRANSPORT HAS COME TO THE CONCLUSION THAT THE CLEAN OUT CAP CAME LOOSE IN TRANSIT BECAUSE THE WASH OUT CAP WASN’T PROPERLY INSPECTED BY THE DRIVER DURING HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION. THE DRIVER FAILED TO MAKE SURE THAT THE WASH OUT CAP WAS ON TIGHT WHICH CAUSED IT TO COME LOOSE IN TRANSIT. WE ARE CONFIDENT ABOUT THIS BECAUSE OUR MAINTENANCE DEPARTMENT INSPECTED THE THREADS ON THE WASH OUT CAP AND THEY WERE IN WORKING ORDER. WE ALSO PRESSURE TESTED THE TRAILER AND IT HELP PRESSURE.    THIS INCIDENT WAS DOCUMENTED IN THE DRIVERS FILE AND HE WENT THROUGH MANDATORY REFRESHER TRAINING ON HOW TO INSPECT A TRAILER. ADDITIONALLY WE SENT OUT A MEMO TO OUR DRIVERS ALERTING THEM ABOUT THIS INCIDENT AND HOW IMPORTANT IT IS TO CHECK AND VERIFY THAT THE CLEAN OUT CAPS ON THE TRAILER ARE IN PLACE AND PROPERLY SECURE. WE WILL ALSO DISCUSS THIS INCIDENT AT OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETING.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: ON THE MORNING OF OCTOBER 15TH, OUR FACILITY LOADED A TRANSPORT TANKER WITH 6447 GALLONS OF CUTBACK ASPHALT USED IN PAVEMENT STABILIZATION/PRIME COATED, CALLED MC-70. THE MC-70 WAS READING 215O F ON THE TEMPERATURE GAUGE, AND WAS LOADED ONTO A TRAILER WHICH HAD PREVIOUSLY HAULED A WATER BASED ASPHALT EMULSION, CRS-2. UPON COMPLETION OF THE LOADING THE TRUCK PULLED ONTO THE SCALE, A DISTANCE COVERED OF APPROXIMATELY 600 FEET. NOTHING UNUSUAL WAS OBSERVED. WHEN THE TRANSPORT LEFT OUR FACILITY, THERE WAS AN APPARENT REACTION OF THE RESIDUAL WATER, RELATIVE TO THE MATERIAL TEMPERATURE. OUR FIRST NOTIFICATION OF THE INCIDENT CAME AS A RESULT OF A PHONE CALL FROM ONE OF OUR NEIGHBORING COMPANIES. I SAW A TRAIL LEADING UP HAZEL STREET, SO I TELEPHONED THE DRIVER’S DISPATCHER TO HALT THE SHIPMENT. I THEN CALLED THE POLICE DEPT. THE POLICE DEPARTMENT THEN CONTACTED THE FIRE DEPT. I CALLED THE CITY OF AKRON STREET DEPT, AND REQUESTED THEIR ASSISTANCE WITH A TRUCK TO SPREAD ABSORBENT SAND. DURING THIS TIME, THE TRANSPORT DRIVER RE-TRACED HIS ROUTE BACK TO THE PLANT, AT WHICH TIME THE TRUCK WAS RE-WEIGHED. WE DISCOVERED THAT THE TRUCK WAS 780 LBS LIGHT OR 99‘’ GALLONS. ONCE THE SAND WAS IN PLACE FOR APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR, THE STREET DEPT THEN PICKED UP THE SAND WITH THEIR BROOM VEHICLES.   THE TRANSPORT TANKER WAS UNLOADED, THEN RELOADED FROM A SECOND AVAILABLE TANK OF THE SAME PRODUCT, WHICH WAS 190O F. HE ARRIVED AT HIS SCHEDULED DESTINATION A FEW HOURS LATE, BUT WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENT.
column169: WE OCCASIONALLY SHIP ELEVATED TEMPERATURE MATERIAL (ABOVE BOILING). WE WILL ONLY LOAD THIS MATERIAL ONTO A TRAILER WHOSE PREVIOUS CONTENTS WERE ALSO ELEVATED TEMP MATERIALS. I.E. ASPHALT CEMENT. THESE TRAILERS CONTAIN NO MOISTURE AND WILL NOT HAVE A REACTION TO OTHER ELEVATED MATERIALS. WE WILL WORK CLOSELY WITH OUR CARRIERS TO ENSURE THE PROPER TRAILER IS SENT TO OUR FACILITY FOR LOADING.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT UNLOADING DESTINATION. CUSTOMER HAD TWO DIESEL TANKS TO DELIVER INTO AND HE WAS A NEWER DRIVER AND WAS UNSURE WHAT TO DO. HE CALLED HIS DISPATCHER FOR INSTRUCTIONS. DISPATCHER CALLED CUSTOMER 24 HOUR NUMBER AND WAS TOLD BY THEIR EMPLOYEE THAT THE TWO TANKS WERE MANIFOLDED TOGETHER AND TO JUST DELIVER INTO ONE TANK AND THEY WOULD FLOW TOGETHER. DURING DELIVERY AN OVER-FILL ALARM WENT OFF AND THE DRIVER ENTERED THE CUSTOMER’S WASH BAY TO VIEW THE VEEDER-ROOT READINGS TO SEE WHERE THE TANK LEVELS WERE AT AND NOTICED ONE WAS FULL. DRIVER WENT BACK OUTSIDE TO SEE TANK WAS OVERFLOWING AND SPILLING. (ABOVE GROUND STORAGE WIND SPILL CONTAINMENT) DRIVER FAILED TO SHUT DOWN LOADING PROCESS AS SOON AS THE ALARM WENT OFF. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN UNLOADING PUMP AND CALLED DISPATCHER OFFICE FOR HELP. EMERGENCY SPILL RESPONSE CO. WAS CALLED TO SCENE.
column169: DRIVER HAD PROPER TRAINING BUT FAILED TO USE HIS BEST JUDGEMENT BY SHUTTING DOWN UNLOADING PROCESS IMMEDIATELY WEN THE OVER-FILL ALARM WENT OFF. HUMAN ERROR WAS WHY THIS SPILL TOOK PLACE AS WELL AS BEING TOLD TO DELIVER INTO ONE FILL PIPE ONLY AND NOT TO SPLIT THE LOAD BETWEEN TWO TANKS.

column25: MARATHON PETROLEUM CORPORATION C/O LYKINS OIL COMPNAY
column168: THE DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF DYED NO. 2 DIESEL TO A JOB SITE IN IVY POINT COMMERCE PARK OFF OF FERGUSON ROAD IN CINCINNATI, OHIO. THE DRIVER WAS IN HIS FINAL STAGES OF COMPLETING THE DELIVERY AND HAD LAID HIS HOSE ON THE GROUND IN ORDER TO PRINT OUT A DELIVERY TICKET FOR THE CUSTOMER. THE DRIVER HAD COMPLETED PUMPING PRODUCT INTO THE CUSTOMER’S JOB TANK AT APPROXIMATELY 3:20PM. THE NOZZLE ON THE HOSE CAME LOOSE AT THE POINT OF SWIVEL AND SUBSEQUENTLY DETACHED FROM THE HOSE ITSELF. THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE LINE BLED OUT AND TRAVELLED INTO A NEARBY STORM DRAIN. THIS STORM DRAIN WAS CONNECTED TO A NEARBY RETENTION POND AND DID NOT TRAVEL INTO ANY OTHER PUBLIC WATERWAYS. THE PRODUCT TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 200 FEET FROM THE POINT OF ENTRY INTO THE STORM DRAIN TO THE BASIN AT THE MOUTH OF THE RETENTION POND.   THE DRIVER, CARRY ABSORBENT PADS, WAS ABLE TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT AT THE BASIN BEFORE IT COULD TRAVEL FURTHER INTO THE RETENTION POND. THE JOB SITE CREW CONTACTED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE COMPANY. COMPANY REPRESENTATIVES CAME ON-SITE AND PROCEEDED TO CONTACT THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT #1130245) AND THE OHIO ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (REPORT #1510-13-2209-1). THE JOB SITE CREW HAS ALSO DEPLOYED OIL-DRY TO THE AFFECTED AREA FROM THE POINT OF DISCHARGE FROM THE HOSE TO THE POINT OF ENTRY INTO THE STORM DRAIN. THE CLERMONT COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY WAS CONTACTED BUT ADVISED THAT THE RESPONDING FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD ALREADY ARRIVED ON THE SCENE. THE COMPANY CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL ENTERPRISES, INC. FOR REMEDIATION.   ENVIRONMENTAL ENTERPRISES, INC. (HEREIN REFERRED TO AS “EEI”) RESPONDED WITH TWO TECHNICIANS AND A “VAC-TRUCK” TO CLEAN THE SPILLED PRODUCT OUT OF THE BASIN OF THE RETENTION POND. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT FLUSHED THE STORM DRAIN, BUT LITTLE TO NO ADDITIONAL PRODUCT WAS FOUND TO HAVE COME THROUGH THE DRAIN INTO THE BASIN. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DEPARTED THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30PM, EEI COMPLETED VACUUMING APPROXIMATELY FIFTEEN MINUTES LATER AND THE COMPANY REPRESENTATIVE DEPARTED AT 8:00PM. EEI DID RETURN TO THE JOB SITE TO CLEAN UP AND DISPOSE OF THE OIL-DRY ON OCTOBER 7. THIS CONCLUDED THE REMEDIATION EFFORT.
column169: FROM BOTH AN OPERATIONAL AND SAFETY PERSPECTIVE, LYKINS OIL COMPANY DOES HOLD QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETINGS WITH THE DRIVERS IN ORDER TO REVIEW A VARIETY OF MECHANICAL AND DELIVERY CONCERNS WITH OUR LINE OF BUSINESS. ALL DRIVERS ARE INSTRUCTED IN PROPER ACTIVITIES, INCLUDING CHECKING FOR DEFECTIVE EQUIPMENT DURING BOTH A PRE-TRIP AND POST-TRIP INSPECTION AND RECORDING ANY FINDINGS. DRIVERS ARE ENCOURAGED TO REPORT TO THEIR SUPERVISOR IF THEY FEEL THERE IS AN ISSUE THAT IS NOT BEING ADDRESSED.  LYKINS OIL COMPANY REVIEWS ALL INCIDENTS TO DETERMINE WHETHER OR NOT SUCH INCIDENTS COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED OR OTHERWISE PREVENTED. IN THIS INSTANCE, LYKINS OIL COMPANY HAS MADE THE DETERMINATION THAT SUCH A DEFECT WITH THE MECHANISM OF DELIVERY COULD HAVE REASONABLE BEEN AVOIDED HAD THE DRIVER PROPERLY CONDUCTED A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION BEFORE PROCEEDING TO MAKE THE SCHEDULED DELIVERIES AND FAILED TO DO SO. WHILE WE ARE PLEASED THAT THE REPERCUSSIONS OF THIS INCIDENT WERE MARGINAL, LYKINS OIL COMPANY HAS BEEN CONDUCTING A REVIEW OF ALL BULK FACILITIES AND VEHICLES’ TO DETERMINE IF THIS MECHANICAL FAILURE IS PRESENT IN ANY OTHER DELIVERY VEHICLES. IN ADDITION, THE DRIVER HAS BEEN REMINDED TO CONDUCT PRE AND POST TRIP INSPECTIONS.   DURING OUR NEXT QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETING OUR DRIVERS WILL BE BRIEFED ON INCIDENT AS WELL AS THE CONSEQUENCES OF THE EMPLOYEES’ ACTIONS. THE DRIVERS WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO CONDUCT MORE EXTENSIVE PRE AND POST TRIP INSPECTIONS AND THEY WILL BE PRESENTED WITH THE EXPECTATION THAT FAILURE TO COMPLY WILL BE THOROUGHLY INVESTIGATED AND ACTED UPON.

column168: A 250 GALLON IBC CONTAINING 250 GALLONS OF GRAMOXONE SL 2.0 (CONTAINING PARAQUAT DICHLORIDE) WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT WHEN BEING UNLOADED AT A FARM. THE RELEASE IS ESTIMATED TO HAVE LASTED LESS THAN 3 MINUTES. THE DAMAGED IBC AS TILTED SO THE REMAINING 200 GALLONS WOULD NOT BE RELEASED. THEN, AN EMPTY IBC WAS MADE AVAILABLE AND THE REMAINING 200 GALLONS IN THE DAMAGED IBC WAS PUMPED INTO THE NEW EMPTY IBC. THE SPILL IMPACTED SOIL ONLY. THE INCIDENT WAS IMMEDIATELY REPORTED TO OUR CORPORATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE OFFICIAL WHO THEN REPORTED IT TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE TEXAS COMMISSION ON ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (TCEQ). SINCE THE SPILL OCCURRED ON ACTIVE FARM LAND, THE TCEQ EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR INDICATED NO OUTSIDE CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WOULD BE NEEDED. AFFECTED SOIL AND GRAVEL WAS EXCAVATED BY THE CARRIER'S EMPLOYEES AND PLACED IN DRUMS, THEN LABELED FOR SHIPMENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY WHERE IT WAS STORED UNTIL SHIPPED OFFSITE FOR DISPOSAL AS NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE ON 12/02/2015. THE EXCAVATION SITE WAS BACKFILLED WITH CLEAN REPLACEMENT MATERIAL. NOTE REGARDING PART II, 13.: SHIP TO ADDRESS ON HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPPING ORDER #12392144 IS PHYSICAL ADDRESS FOR JEREMY LOUDER; THE IBC WAS DELIVERED TO THE FARM PROPERTY LOCATED OFF COUNTY ROAD 415 IN LOMAX, HOWARD COUNTY, TEXAS.
column169: ALL EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE SHIPPING AND HANDLING OF ALL MATERIALS HANDLED BY HELENA CHEMICAL COMPANY ARE TRAINED YEARLY ON FORKLIFT OPERATION AND SAFETY. EMPLOYEES ARE CONTINUALLY REMINDED ABOUT PROPER FORKLIFT OPERATION AND SAFETY. THIS INCIDENT HAS SHOWN THAT ADDITIONAL FOLLOW-UP TRAINING IS NECESSARY AND IS SCHEDULED FOR THE NEXT ROUTINE SAFETY MEETING. WE HAVE ALSO IDENTIFIED THAT BESIDES ADDITIONAL TRAINING, IT IS HELPFUL TO HAVE A "SPOTTER" PRESENT TO HELP THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR WHEN LOADING/UNLOADING TRUCKS, ESPECIALLY AT CUSTOMER LOCATIONS WHERE THE TERRAIN IS LESS FAMILIAR THAN AT OUR OWN FACILITIES.

column168: On 10/23/15 at 11:15 AM, our driver exited US 41 Northbound at the Lineville Road exit in Suamico, Wl. He entered the round-a-bout at the top of the off-ramp with excessive speed. The excessive speed caused the tractor and trailer to roll-over onto the passenger side of the vehicle. The resulting roll-over caused the rear pocket of the trailer to breach because of crushing/abrasion/puncture. This resulted in approx. 705 gallons of diesel fuel to be released slowly onto the roadway. By the time the driver safely exited the vehicle, the County Sheriff Deputy was arriving and within a couple minutes of that, the Suamico Fire Department arrived as well. The fire dept initialized the clean-up. They called a neighboring municipality (Village of Howard) and requested assistance from their street depart that was working nearby with a front end loader and trucks of sand. They were able to contain the majority of the spill on the concrete roadway with the sand and spill booms. A small quantity (less than 50 gallons) entered a storm basin next to the roadway. Within 1.5 hours, an environmental company, SECSI based in Green  Bay arrived to continue with the clean-up. Employees from Garrow Oil & Klemm Tank Lines proceeded to pump off the fuel on the trailer into a 2nd tanker truck. This was completed within 3.5 hours. The truck was then rolled up-right with 2 large tow trucks. The tractor and trailer were then towed to our shop approx. 2 miles away. A second remediation company, North Shore Environmental Construction, based in Germantown, WI arrived within 4 hours to finish the clean-up process. They completed that process by 7 PM that evening. SECSI returned on 10/26/15 to inspect the site one last time and remove some absorbent socks left in the storm basin over the weekend. A SERTS (substance release notification report) was delivered to the Wisconsin DNR on 12/2/15 and the DNR accepted and closed it's SERTS on12/10/15.
column169: Even though we have indented this accident/incident to be an isolated case of errant judgment by our driver of record, nonetheless, we have been accountable to the reality that maybe a gap has opened up within our safety management program. Consequently, a meeting was held with all of our professional operators to review this accident and all the component parts and persons that went to make up this incident, along with the time-line of events leading up to it. Each operator was given an opportunity to visit out-loud about any and all concerns regarding safety at Garrow Oil, and to our surprise, all of the feed back was extremely positive. We again hammered them all on the negative ramifications that can occur when excessive speed is the order of the day. A promise was put forth to all, that prior to the end of the year, the safety department would be doing a ride along with all drivers in order to reconcile skill levels and acumen. Lastly, our operators were told that the safety department would also be doing more visual inspections in the field, with the intention of observing all operators doing everything right.

column168: WHILE ENTERING LOADING RACK AT SUNOCO LOGISTICS IN SINKING SPRINGS (MONTICELLO), PA DRIVER FAILED TO REDUCE SPEED, STRIKING A BOLSTER PROTECTING THE ELECTRONIC GATE ALONG WITH THE GATE. THE GATE PUNCTURED THE THIRD COMPARTMENT OF THE FOUR COMPARTMENT TRAILER. THE PUNCTURE WAS LOCATED MIDWAY OF THE COMPARTMENT ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 400 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT TO LEAK ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT. DUE TO THE SIZE OF THE PARKING AREA SUNOCO PERSONNEL WERE ABLE TO CONFINE THE SPILL TO THE ASPHALT. BERKS COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED, CLOSED FRITZTOWN ROAD AND FOAMED PARKING LOT AREA. STREET WAS CLOSED FROM APPROXIMATELY 14:30 TO 19:00 HOURS. (FRITZTOWN ROAD IS NOT A MAJOR ARTERY HOWEVER IT ALLOWS TRANSIT TO LOCAL TRAFFIC TO AND FROM SINKING SPRING.) IN THE PROCESS OF FOAMING THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PUSHED FOAM AND ETHANOL MIX ONTO A SOILED (DIRT) AREA. SUNOCO CALLED LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND FOR CLEANUP. ON ARRIVAL APPROX. 1600 HRS. LEWIS USED ABSORBENT PADS AND VACUUMED PARKING LOT REMOVING ETHANOL. THE SOIL WAS CHECKED SEVERAL TIMES OVER THE NEXT FEW DAYS AND THERE WAS NOT ANY ISSUES. AT NO TIME DID ANY PRODUCT ENTER ANY STREAMS, WATERWAYS, SEWERS, OUT-FALLS, ETC. ALL RESIDUAL AND CLEANING MATERIAL WAS DRUMMED AND DISPOSED OF BY LEWIS AT A LICENSED FACILITY. THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES. REMAINING PRODUCT IN 3RD COMPARTMENT WAS METERED OFF AT WHICH TIME GALLONS WERE DETERMINED BY SUNOCO PERSONNEL. ON SITE AFTER THE SPILL OCCURRED WAS PENNSYLVANIA DEP(KRISTOPHER GILHAM 610.916.0100). BERKS COUNTY EMS, MATTHEW STRIKER, 610.374.4800. X8215). FEMA REP FOR BERKS COUNTY (NAME UNKNOWN) ALONG WITH NUMEROUS OTHER PERSONNEL. RESPONDING TO TO THE SPILL FOR PENN TANK LINES, 1500HRS. APPROX. PAUL OOTEN, REGIONAL MGR. (954.332.8015) AND 1700 HRS. APPROX, LARRY DALTON, SENIOR FIELD SAFETY SUPERVISOR, (412.292.2571).
