column168: AN ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANK WAS BEING DELIVERED TO A FARM FIELD WHEN THE HINCH PIN SHEARED, CAUSING THE NURSE TANK TO VIOLENTLY STRIKE THE HIGHWAY SURFACE. THIS TANK WAS PURCHASED RECENTLY AND THIS WAS IT FIRST TIME BEING FILLED AND SHIPPED. INITIALLY, IT WAS BELIEVED THE TANK WAS PUNCTURE WHEN THE HINCH PIN SHEARED SO COMPANY RESPONDERS WERE NOT ALLOWED TO APPROACH THE TANK. ONCE THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA VAPORS DISSIPATED WITHIN APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES, COMPANY RESPONDERS WERE ABLE TO INSPECT THE TANK AND DETERMINED THE FIX LIQUID GAUGE WAS TRANSPORTED FROM THE INCIDENT SCENE ON US ROUTE 67 TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY IN ADAIR IL. THE FOLLOWING MORNING, THE TANK WAS RE-WEIGHTED AND IT WAS DETERMINED A TOTAL OF 60 POUNDS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS RELEASED FORM THE TANK IN THE INCIDENT ( SEE VOIDED SCALE TICKET #14211). A COMPLETE VISUAL INSPECTION WAS COMPLETED AND THE TANK WAS PUT BACK INTO SERVICE ON NOVEMBER 2, 2015 WITH NO ADDITIONAL ISSUES.   NOTE REGARDING WAYBILL/ SHIPPER PAPER. DUE TO THE NATURE OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA RETAIL ALES TO FARMERS 17 TO 20 SHIPMENTS WERE MADE TO THE SAME CUSTOMER'S FIELD OVER APPROXIMATELY FIVE WEEKS. A SINGLE INVOICE AND SHIPPING PAPER WAS GENERATED WITH NUMBER 122736146 ON DECEMBER 8 2015, REFLECTING THE TOTAL VOLUME SHIPPED. EACH INDIVIDUAL SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF A SINGLE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANK HOLDING APPROXIMATELY 850 GALLONS. AVERAGING 4386 LBS AND WAS ACCOMPANIED BY A WEIGHT TICKET AND GENERIC SHIPPING PAPER REFLECTING THE UN IDENTIFICATION NUMBER AND PROPER SHIPPING NAME FOR THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA.

column168: THE CRYOGENIC TRANSPORT, LLC UNIT WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON STATE ROAD 37 ON CRAWFORD COUNTY, INDIANA. THE DRIVER INDICATED THAT A VEHICLE TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON STATE ROAD 37 WENT LEFT OF CENTER. IN ORDER TO AVOID AN IMPACT WITH THIS VEHICLE, THE CRYOGENIC TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER ADVISED HE SWERVED TO THE RIGHT. THE UNIT WENT OFF THE ROADWAY AND ROLLED OVER. THE TRAILER HAULING APPROXIMATELY 4800 GALLONS OF LIQUID OXYGEN WAS NOT COMPROMISED. IN ORDER TO SAFELY UPRIGHT THE UNIT, SAFETY PERSONNEL MADE THE DECISION TO VENT THE OXYGEN INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. AS AN EXTRA PRECAUTION, SAFETY FORCES CLOSED THE ROADWAY AND EVACUATED TWO NEARBY HOMES. THERE WAS ULTIMATELY NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

column168: VEHICLE 1 (V01) WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE 75 IN LANE 1. VEHICLE 2 (V02) WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON I-75 IN LANE #2. VEHICLE 3 (V03) WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND IN LANE #4.   AS RESULT OF THE LOSS OF CONTROL OF V01 DURING A LANE CHANGE, V01 TRAVELED ACROSS LANE NUMBER 2 IN PATH OF V02 CAUSING DRIVER-2 TO APPLY V02 BRAKES TO AVOID COLLIDING WITH V01. V01 THEN TRAVELED INTO LANE 4 WHERE V01 RIGHT SIDE FRONT COLLIDED WITH V03 LEFT FRONT .  V01 LEFT SIDE THEN COLLIDED WITH V02 RIGHT SIDE AS V02 WAS BRAKING ACROSS NORTHBOUND LANES THAN ONTO THE RIGHT MEDIAN WHERE V02 OVERTURNED ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE.   V01 ALSO TRAVELED ONTO THE RIGHT MEDIAN WHERE V01 FRONT COLLIDED WITH V02 UNDERCARRIAGE. UPON POLICE ARRIVAL, V01 REMAINED AGAINST V01 UNDERCARRIAGE, VEHICLE 02 REMAINED ON ITS LEFT SIDE WITH DRIVER -2 TRAPPED INSIDE V01 AND V03 REMAINED AT FINAL REST ON THE RIGHT MEDIAN.   COLLISION CAUSED V02 CARGO TANK TO SPILL APPROXIMATELY 600 GALLONS OF ITS CARGO LOAD OF HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION HAVING BROWARD SHERIFFS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM TO RESPOND TO SCENE TO CONTROL THE LEAKAGE AS WELL AS FREE DRIVER-2 FROM THE WRECKAGE.

column168: THIS COLLISION OCCURRED ON I-60 SOUTHBOUND, NORTH OF THE SHERIDAN RD. V-2 WAS STOPPED PARTIALLY IN THE #4 LANE AND RIGHT SHOULDER WITH REAR FLASHING LIGHTS ACTIVATED. V-1 WAS TRAVELING IN THE #4 LANE AT APPROXIMATELY 35 MILES PER HOUR AND APPROACHING V-2 FROM A DISTANCE OF 200 METERS AWAY. FOR AN UNKNOWN REASON, P-1 FAILED TO OBSERVE V-2 PARTIALLY BLOCKING THE #4 LANE. P-1 FAILED TO STOP OR MERGE V-1 LEFT, AND THE RIGHT SIDE OF V-1 COLLIDED INTO THE LEFT SIDE OF V-2. AFTER THE COLLISION, V-2 WAS PUSHED TO THE RIGHT AND CAME TO REST IN THE DIRT AREA. V-1 BECAME DISABLED AND CAME TO REST, BLOCKING THE #4 LANE RIGHT SHOULDER AND DIRT AREA. DUE TO THE COLLISION, V-1 BEGAN LEAKING ETHANOL PRODUCT FROM THE CARGO TANK AREA. P-1 EXITED HIS VEHICLE AND WAITED FOR ASSISTANCE.     THE SUMMARY WAS BASED ON THE DRIVER'S STATEMENTS AND VEHICLE DAMAGE.
column169: 100% DRIVER ERROR. HE WAS FIRED FOR THE INCIDENT.

column168: ANOTHER CAR MADE A U TURN ON HIGHWAY. OUR TRUCK WENT TO THE SIDE TO MISS THE CAR. THE DITCH WAS SOFT AND SUCKED THE TRUCK DOWN INTO THE DITCH WHICH MADE THE DRIVER LOOSE CONTROL AND ROLL OVER.

column168: NATHANIEL BROWN (JONESCO TRUCKING) WAS HEADING SOUTH BOND ON ST 77 HEADING TO SHOWLOW AZ. WHEN A DRUNK DRIVER THAT WAS HEADING NORTH BOUND CAME HEAD ON IN TO NATHANIEL'S LANE. NATHANIEL MOVED OVER ON THE SHOULDER TO TRY AND AVOID CONTACT. THE DRUNK DRIVER ENDED UP HITTING NATHANIEL. AFTER THE CONTACT WITH THE DRUNK DRIVER NATHANIEL LOSS CONTROL OF THE TRUCK AND ENDED UP ROLLING THE TRUCK AND TRAILER MULTIPLE TIMES.     AZ DPS HAZMAT TEAM WAS CALLED OUT TO TAKE CONTROL OF THE ACCIDENT AND HELP WITH THE CLEAN UP. JONESCOS MANAGEMENT TEAM WAS NOTIFIED AND STARTED WORKING WITH THEIR INSURANCE COMPANY AND KERRY ENVIRONMENT ON THE CLEAN UP. KERRY ENVIRONMENT WAS RELIVED BY ERI AND THEY HANDLED THE REST OF THE CLEAN UP.
column169: WE HAVE CONDUCTED ADVANCE DRIVER TRAINING WITH MOST OF OUR DRIVERS PUT ON BY OUR INSURANCE COMPANY ENERGI. AS WE HAVE CONDUCTED ROLLOVER PREVENTION TRAINING WITH ALL OF OUR DRIVERS. WE CONTINUE TO HOLD OUR QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETINGS WITH ALL OF OUR DRIVERS.
